{{Infobox member of the Knesset |Name = David Stern |image = |birth_date = 29 March 1910 |birth_place = [[Suwałki]], [[Russian Empire]] |Year of Aliyah = 1935 |death_date = {{Death date and age|2003|2|13|1910|3|29|df=y}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|9]] |party1 = [[Likud]] |partyyears1 = 1979–1981 }}[[Image:Grave of David Stern.JPG|thumb|right|Stern's grave in the Nahlat Yitzhak cemetery]]
'''David Stern''' ({{Lang-he-n|דוד שטרן}}, 29 March 1910 – 13 February 2003) was an [[Israel]]i businessman and politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Likud]] between 1979 and 1981.
==Biography== Stern was born in [[Suwałki]] in the [[Russian Empire]] (today in [[Poland]]) in 1910. During [[World War I]] his mother fled the Germans with him and his brother, [[Avraham Stern|Avraham]], and found refuge with her sister in [[Russia]]. Stern studied engineering in [[Brno]] in [[Czechoslovakia]]. He made [[aliyah]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1935, and became a member of [[Lehi (group)|Lehi]], of which Avraham was the leader.
He worked as a building contractor, and was president of the Building Contractors Association.
A member of the [[Herut]] central committee, he became a member of [[Tel Aviv]] city council in 1969. He was on the Likud list (an alliance of Herut and other right-wing parties) for the [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|1977 elections]], but failed to win a seat. However, he entered the Knesset on 18 June 1979 as a replacement for [[Shmuel Rechtman]],<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mkindexByKnesset_eng.asp?knesset=9 Knesset Members in the Ninth Knesset] Knesset website</ref> who had resigned his seat after failing in an appeal against a conviction for bribery. Stern lost his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|1981 elections]].
He died in 2003 at the age of 92.
